0.body: Strata is a dynamic and sleek Wayland compositor and window manager for GNU/Linux systems. It's written completely in Rust using the Smithay library. Strata is made to be modular. It is done this way so that you, the user can mix N match different components to make Strata work the way you want. Strata follows this architecture, which is inspired by BSPWM : ╭───────────────╮ ╭───────────╮ ╭──────────╮ │ Hotkey Daemon │ ────> │ StrataCTL │ ────> │ StrataWM │ ╰───────────────╯ ╰───────────╯ ╰──────────╯ This makes it possible so that you can interchange components, for example, instead of using Kagi, the official Strata hotkey daemon, you can use SWHKD or even make your own. As Strata grows in complexity, this architecture will, hopefully, prove to be useful.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: StrataWM is a Wayland Compositor , which is very different from an X11 Window Manager. In this case, Strata is on the same level as X11. Strata is the name of the whole Strata project, which is also interchangebly used to reference the compositor. The whole Strata project includes: StrataWM - The Wayland Compositor. StrataCTL - The command line interface for controlling StrataWM and, Kagi - The official hotkey daemon that listens for keypresses and executes commands.

13.body:
Description - General settings for Strata Values - workspaces - Number of total workspaces in_gaps - Gaps between windows out_gaps - Gaps outside window edges kb_repeat - Repeat settings for keyboard in the form [repeat_delay, repeat_rate] where repeat_delay is the amount of time before the pressed key starts auto repeating (in ms) and repeat_rate is the delay between each repeat key press Default Values - [general]
workspaces = 9
in_gaps = 4
out_gaps = 8
kb_repeat = [500, 250]
13.title: general

14.body:
Description - Decorations for windows Values - border_width - The width of the window border in pixels. border_active - The color of the border when the window is active. border_inactive - The color of the border when the window is inactive. border_radius - The radius of the window corners in pixels. window_opacity - The opacity of the window, ranging from 0.0 (completely transparent) to 1.0 (fully opaque). blur_enable - A boolean value indicating whether window blur is enabled. blur_size - The size of the window blur effect in pixels. blur_passes - The number of blur passes to apply to the window. More the passes, more refined is the blur. blur_optimization - A boolean value indicating whether optimization is applied to the blur effect. shadows_enabled - A boolean value indicating whether window shadows are enabled. shadow_size - The size of the window shadow in pixels. shadow_blur - The blur level of the window shadow. shadow_color - The color of the window shadow. Default Values - [window_decorations]
border_width = 2
border_active = "#FFF"
border_inactive = "#131418"
border_radius = 5
window_opacity = 0.9
blur_enable = true
blur_size = 2
blur_passes = 2
blur_optimization = true
shadows_enabled = true
shadow_size = 4
shadow_blur = 3
shadow_color = "#FFF"
14.title: window_decorations

5.title: 1. Clone the repository

6.body: There is a a script that installs both StrataWM and StrataCTL. To run it, cd into the cloned repo: cd stratawm then add executable permissions to the script: chmod +x install.sh finally, run the script: ./install.sh You can sit back and relax while it installs Strata. It might take a bit of time since it has to compile the source code and all the dependencies but if your system is a bit better than a potato, this won't take much time.
6.breadcrumbs: StrataWM » Getting Started » Compiling from Source » 2. Installing using the script
6.title: 2. Installing using the script

7.body: To install manually, cd into the cloned repo and then run: cargo install --path . This'll install it for your user. If you want to install it globally (which is not recommended right now), then run: sudo cargo install --path . Now you have to install StrataCTL. Without it StrataWM is almost unusable. First clone the repo: git clone https://github.com/stratawm/stratactl Then cd into it: cd stratactl And finally install it: cargo install --path . If you want to install it globally, then run: sudo cargo install --path .
7.breadcrumbs: StrataWM » Getting Started » Compiling from Source » 3. Installing manually
7.title: 3. Installing manually

8.body: Congratulations, if all went well, you should have StrataWM and StrataCTL installed on your system. Next you'd want to install Kagi or a hotkey daemon of your choice. If you want to install Kagi, go to the chapter on the left hand side for compiling from source. Then next chapter will teach you how to configure Strata.
8.breadcrumbs: StrataWM » Getting Started » Compiling from Source » 4. Next steps
